  <discussion>Lygodesmia grandiflora is recognized mainly by its relatively large corollas. Some variants were segregated as distinct species by A. S. Tomb; because of intermediates, putative hybrids, and associated identification problems, it is probably best to recognize these as varieties pending further investigation (A. Cronquist 1994; S. L. Welsh et al. 2003).</discussion>
  <couplet>1.Phyllaries 8–12; florets 8–122a. Lygodesmia grandiflora var. grandiflora</couplet>
  <couplet>1.Phyllaries 5(–6); florets 5(–7).</couplet>
  <couplet>2.Corollas white (may turn pinkish when dry); stems (woody) branched from bases; leaves stiff, spreading; involucre apices spreading 2e. Lygodesmia grandiflora var. entrada</couplet>
  <couplet>2.Corollas lavender, pink, purple, rose, or white; stems simple or branched from bases or distally (if branched from bases, either leaves lax or plants from vicinity of Moab, Utah); involucre apices narrow.</couplet>
  <couplet>3.Stems much branched from bases; proximal leaves narrow, linear-filiform, 1–3 mm wide, rigid2d. Lygodesmia grandiflora var. doloresensis</couplet>
  <couplet>3.Stems simple or sparsely branched from bases or distally; proximal leaves lanceolate to linear-subulate, (2–)3–6 mm wide, ± lax (widespread in southwestern states).</couplet>
